<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find the magnitude and direction of 
      <ol marker ="a.">
        <li>
          <m>\vec{a}+\vec{b}</m>
        </li>
        <li><m>\vec{a}-\vec{b}</m></li>
      </ol>
      if <m>\vec{a}=3\hat{i}+4\hat{j} +2\hat{k}</m> and <m>\vec{b}=4\hat{i}-\hat{j} -2\hat{k}.</m>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <ol marker ="a.">
        <li>
          <m>\vec{a}+\vec{b} =7\hat{i}+3\hat{j}</m>
          <me>
            | \vec{a}+\vec{b} |= \sqrt{(\vec{a}+\vec{b})\cdot (\vec{a}+\vec{b})} = \sqrt{49+9}=\sqrt{58}
          </me>
        </li>
        <li><m>\vec{a}-\vec{b} =-\hat{i}+5\hat{j}+4\hat{k}</m>
        <me>
          | \vec{a}-\vec{b} |= \sqrt{(\vec{a}-\vec{b})\cdot (\vec{a}-\vec{b})} = \sqrt{1+25+16}=\sqrt{42}
        </me>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>


<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      The magnitude of two vectors <m>\vec{a}</m> and <m>\vec{b}</m> are 20 and 40, respectively. 
      Vector <m>\vec{a}</m> is pointed along <m>20^{o}</m> north of east and vector <m>\vec{b}</m> is pointed along 
      <m>230^{o}</m> south of west. Find the magnitude and direction of <image source="fig2gi.png" width="30%"> </image>
      <ol marker ="a.">
        <li>
          <m>\vec{a}+\vec{b}</m>
        </li>
        <li><m>\vec{a}-\vec{b}</m></li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      This problem can be solved by two different ways, one way is using head and tail rules as
      shown in figure, <image source="fig2gii.png" width="30%"> </image> here
      <me>
        \vec{c}=\vec{a}+\vec{b}
      </me>
      its magnitude can be found by using relation <fn>see appendix</fn>
      <me>
        c =\sqrt{a^{2}+b^{2}+2ab\cos\theta}
      </me>
      <me>
        =\sqrt{20^{2}+40^{2}+2\times 20\times 40\times \cos 150^{o}} = 24.78
      </me>
      its direction can be found by using relation
      <me>
        \phi=\tan^{-1}\left(\frac{b\sin\theta}{a+b\cos\theta}\right) = -53^{o}-20^{o}=-73^{o}\quad \text{(S of W)}
      </me>
      We add <m>20^{o}</m> in <m>\phi</m> to find the direction of resultant vector from x-axis.
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>Another way</em> is to resolved these two vectors into component vectors 
      and then find resultant of the corresponding components along x and y axes.
      From figure, <image source="fig2giii.png" width="30%"> </image>  we have 
      <me>
        a_{x}=a\cos\theta_{1} = 20\cos 20^{o}=18.79;\quad a_{y}=a\sin\theta_{1}=20\sin 20^{o} = 6.84
      </me>
      <me>
        b_{x}=b\cos\theta_{2}= 40\cos 50^{o}=25.71;\quad b_{y}=b\sin\theta_{2}=40\sin 50^{o}=30.64
      </me>
      <me>
        \therefore\quad R_{x}=a_{x}-b_{x} = -6.92 \quad \text{and}\quad R_{y}=a_{y}-b_{y} =-23.8
      </me>
      Hence <m>R = 24.78</m>, and <m>\phi = \tan^{-1}\left(\frac{R_{y}}{R_{x}}\right)= 73.78^{o}</m> (S of W).
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find the magnitude of a vector <m>\vec{c}</m> in the vector equation 
      <m>\vec{a}+2\vec{b}-3\vec{c}=-4\hat{j}</m>, where <m>\vec{a} =\hat{i}-2\hat{k}</m> 
      and <m>\vec{b} =-\hat{j}+\hat{k}</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <me>
        \vec{a}+2\vec{b}-3\vec{c}=-4\hat{j}
      </me>
      <me>
        \text{or,}\quad (\hat{i}-2\hat{k}) +2(-\hat{j}+\hat{k})-3\vec{c}=-4\hat{j} 
      </me>
      <me>
        \text{or,}\quad  -3\vec{c}=-4\hat{j}-\hat{i}+2\hat{k} +2\hat{j}-2\hat{k}=-\hat{i} -2\hat{j}
      </me>
      <me>
        \text{or,}\quad  \vec{c} = \frac{1}{3}(\hat{i}+2\hat{j})
      </me>
      <me>
        \therefore \quad |\vec{c}| = c = \sqrt{\frac{1}{9}(1+4)} = \sqrt{\frac{5}{9}} =\frac{1}{3}\sqrt{5}
      </me>
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Show that the distance between points in a plane do not change by rotating a coordinate system.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
        <p>
          Let p and q be two points in space. Now from figure, <image source="fig2h.png" width="30%"> </image> we have -
         <me> x'=OL'=r\cos\phi </me> 
         <me> \text{and} \quad y'= PL'=r\sin\phi</me>. 
      <me>
        \text{Also} \quad x =OL=r\cos (\theta+\phi)
       </me>
       <me>
        \text{and} \quad y= PL=r\sin (\theta+\phi)
       </me>
      <me>
        \text{Now,} \quad x=r(\cos\theta\cos\phi-\sin\theta\sin\phi)=r\cos\phi\cos\theta-r\sin\phi\sin\theta
       </me>
       <me>
        \therefore\quad x = x'\cos\theta -y'\sin\theta
       </me> 
<me>
  \text{Again,} \quad y=r(\sin\theta\cos\phi-\cos\theta\sin\phi)=r\cos\phi\sin\theta+r\sin\phi\cos\theta
</me>
<me>
\therefore\quad y = x'\sin\theta +y'\cos\theta
</me>
     </p>
     <p>
      On solving these equations we get -
      <me>
        x' = x\cos\theta + y\sin\theta
      </me>
      <me>
        \text{and}\quad y' = -x\sin\theta + y\cos\theta 
      </me>
The distance between points <m>p(x_{1},y_{1})</m> and <m>q(x_{2},y_{2})</m> in xy coordinate system is given by
<me>
  d=pq=\sqrt{(x_{2}-x_{1})^{2}+(y_{2}-y_{1})^{2}}
</me>
<me>
  =\sqrt{[(x'_{2}-x'_{1})\sin\theta + (y'_{2}-y'_{1})\cos\theta}]^{2} =\sqrt{(x'_{2}-x'_{1})^{2}+ (y'_{2}-y'_{1})^{2}} 
</me>
which is the distance between points <m>p(x'_{1},y'_{1})</m> and <m>q(x'_{2},y'_{2})</m> in x' y' coordinate system, 
i.e., the distance between two points is invariant upon the rotation of a coordinate system.
     </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<example>
