<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Two points <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> in the xy plane have the respective Cartesian 
      and polar coordinates <m>(3 \,m, - 4\, m)</m> and <m>(15 \,m, 30^{o})</m>. 
      <ol marker ="a.">
        <li>
          What are the polar coordinates of the first point? 
        </li>
        <li>
          What are the rectangular coordinates of the second point?
        </li>
        <li>
          What is the distance between the two points?
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <ol marker ="a.">
        <li>
          <m>(5m,-53.13^{o})</m>
           <me>
            <term>Use:</term>  A=\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}} ; \quad \theta = tan^{-1}\left(\frac{-4}{3}\right)
          </me>
        </li>
        <li>
          <m>(13\,m,7.5\,m)</m>
          <me>
            <term>Use:</term> x=B\cos\theta;\quad y=B\sin\theta
          </me>
        </li>
        <li>
          <me>
            AB=\sqrt{(x_{2}-x_{1})^{2}+(y_{2}-y_{1})^{2}}=15.24\,m.
          </me>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>
<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Prove that <m>|\vec{A}+\vec{B} | = |\vec{A}-\vec{B}| </m>, only when <m>\vec{A}</m> and 
      <m>\vec{B} </m> are perpendicular to each other.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      Consider 
      <me>
        \vec{r} = r_{x}\hat{i} + r_{y}\hat{j} + r_{z}\hat{k} 
      </me>
      then  
      <me>
        |\vec{r}|  = \sqrt{\vec{r}\cdot\vec{r}}= \sqrt{r_{x}^{2} + r_{y}^{2}+r_{z}^{2}}.
      </me>
Now,
<me>
  \vec{A}+\vec{B} = (A_{x}\hat{i}+ A_{y}\hat{j} +A_{z}\hat{k} ) + (B_{x}\hat{i}+ B_{y}\hat{j} +B_{z}\hat{k})
</me>
<me>
  = (A_{x}+B_{x})\hat{i} + (A_{y}+B_{y})\hat{j} + (A_{z}+B_{z})\hat{k}
</me>
and 
<me>
  \vec{A}\cdot\vec{B} = |\vec{A}||\vec{B}|\cos\theta  = A_{x}B_{x} + A_{y}B_{y} + A_{z}B_{z}
</me>
if <m>\theta = 0</m>. 
      but,
      <me>
        \vec{A}\cdot\vec{B} = |\vec{A}||\vec{B}|\cos\theta  = 0 
      </me>
      if <m>\theta = 90^{o}</m>. Therefore,
      <me>
        |\vec{A}+\vec{B}| =\sqrt{(\vec{A}+\vec{B})\cdot (\vec{A}+\vec{B})} 
      </me>
      <me>
        = \sqrt{(A_{x}^2 + B_{x}^2+ 2 A_{x}B_{x}\cos\theta) + (A_{y}^2 + B_{y}^2+ 2 A_{y}B_{y}\cos\theta) + (A_{z}^2 + B_{z}^2+ 2 A_{z}B_{z}\cos\theta)} 
      </me>
      <men xml:id="eqn-exam2i">
        \therefore \quad |\vec{A}+\vec{B}| = \sqrt{(A_{x}^2 + A_{y}^2 + A_{z}^2) + (B_{x}^2 + B_{y}^2 + B_{z}^2)} 
      </men>
    </p>
    <p>

Similarly, 
<me>
  |\vec{A}-\vec{B}| =\sqrt{(\vec{A}-\vec{B})\cdot (\vec{A}-\vec{B})} 
</me>
<me>
  = \sqrt{(A_{x}^2 + B_{x}^2- 2 A_{x}B_{x}\cos\theta) + (A_{y}^2 + B_{y}^2- 2 A_{y}B_{y}\cos\theta) + (A_{z}^2 + B_{z}^2-2 A_{z}B_{z}\cos\theta)}
</me>
<men xml:id="eqn-exam2ii">
  \therefore \quad |\vec{A}-\vec{B}| = \sqrt{(A_{x}^2 + A_{y}^2 + A_{z}^2) + (B_{x}^2 + B_{y}^2 + B_{z}^2) } 
</men>
Hence from <xref first="eqn-exam2i" last="eqn-exam2ii"/>, it is clear that 
<me>
  |\vec{A}+\vec{B}| = |\vec{A}-\vec{B}|
</me>
If and only if <m>\vec{A}</m> and <m>\vec{B}</m> are perpendicular.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find the condition at which <m> |\vec{A}-\vec{B}| = |\vec{A}| - |\vec{B}| </m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <me>
        |\vec{A}-\vec{B}| =\sqrt{(\vec{A}-\vec{B})\cdot (\vec{A}-\vec{B})}
      </me>
      <me>
        = \sqrt{(A_{x}^2 + B_{x}^2- 2 A_{x}B_{x}\cos\theta) + (A_{y}^2 + B_{y}^2- 2 A_{y}B_{y}\cos\theta) + (A_{z}^2 + B_{z}^2-2 A_{z}B_{z}\cos\theta)}
      </me>
           <me>
        = \sqrt{(A_{x}^2 + A_{y}^2 + A_{z}^2 )+ (B_{x}^2 + B_{y}^2 + B_{z}^2)- 2\cos\theta(A_{x}B_{x}+A_{y}B_{y}+A_{z}B_{z})}
      </me>
 If <m>\theta = 0^{o}</m>, then <m>\cos\theta = 1 </m>.
Therefore, 
<me>
  |\vec{A}-\vec{B}|  = \sqrt{(A_{x}^2 + A_{y}^2 + A_{z}^2 )+ (B_{x}^2 + B_{y}^2 + B_{z}^2)- 2(A_{x}B_{x}+A_{y}B_{y}+A_{z}B_{z})}
</me>
or,
<me>
  |\vec{A}-\vec{B}|  = \sqrt{|\vec{A}^{2}|+ |\vec{B}^{2}|- 2|\vec{A}| |\vec{B}|} = \sqrt{(|\vec{A}| - |\vec{B}|)^{2}}= |\vec{A}| - |\vec{B}|
</me>
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>
